  {
    "id": "ce2016-q044",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "data-structures-algorithms",
    "subtopic": "binary-search-tree",
    "stem": "A Binary Tree is considered a Binary Search Tree if:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "The key in each node is greater than all keys stored in the left sub-tree, and smaller than all keys in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "The key in each node is smaller than all keys stored in the left sub-tree, and greater than all keys in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "The key in a parent node is greater than all keys of its children nodes.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "For each node, the number of nodes in left sub-tree is equal to the number of nodes in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "The BST invariant is that for every node, all keys in its left subtree are smaller and all keys in its right subtree are larger, which is option A and is what makes an in-order traversal come out sorted. Option B inverts the ordering, C describes a max-heap, and D describes a balanced (not a search) tree; a BST need not be balanced.",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 44
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "ca1c4298537bf5a57b095e94a16a540c2bc4cf98"
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q045",
    "type": "true_false",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "ram",
    "stem": "RAM cell is associated with identifier called address.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "True.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "False.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "True. Memory is organised as cells, each with a unique numeric address, and it is precisely this addressability that lets the CPU reach any cell directly in constant time, which is what 'random access' means.",
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 45
